s":[],"reads":[]}','[{"depth":2,"text":"Places","anchor":"places"},{"depth":2,"text":"Holds","anchor":"holds"},{"depth":2,"text":"Pairs","anchor":"pairs"},{"depth":2,"text":"Traces","anchor":"traces"},{"depth":2,"text":"Nests","anchor":"nests"},{"depth":2,"text":"Reads","anchor":"reads"},{"depth":2,"text":"Carries","anchor":"carries"}]',225,'sha256:cdf731609bfc780697eae9bbd35cd2e753a0bd8783ce417b8859a7273615bd15','1970-01-01','2026-06-25');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO entries (id,title,slug,source_path,public_url,content,plain_text,excerpt,status,garden_status,grounded,entry_order,entry_type,branch,aliases,tags,related,structure,headings,word_count,content_hash,created,updated) VALUES ('first.threshold','Threshold','threshold','Reality_Mechanics/1_First/Boundary Conditions/Threshold.md','https://atlas.realitymechanics.nz/threshold.html','# Threshold

Threshold names a boundary condition under strain where change becomes readable. It is not a measurement, line, or quantitative cutoff — it names the held change-limit within the current scope of evaluation. Threshold sits between boundary, strain, and bearing: distinction is located, strain is present, and something is at the point where it can either hold or [[Shift|shift]] without yet being determined either way.

## Places

Threshold places a boundary condition under strain at the point where change becomes readable.

## Holds

Threshold is held by [[Boundary]] and [[Strain]]. Distinction must be located and under contrast before its change-limit can be read.

## Pairs

Asymmetry carries downward — into [[Capacity]] and [[Enter]]. Threshold is the change-limit under strain: it names the point where crossing becomes readable, not a lateral juncture requiring a co-present condition.

## Traces

- [[Boundary]]
- [[Strain]]
- [[Shift]]

## Nests

Threshold nests as a boundary condition. It sits between strain and bearing without becoming the crossing between orders by itself.

## Reads

Threshold becomes recognisable where a boundary condition under strain can be read as change-limit — where something is present at the point of potential shift without yet having crossed or entered it.

## Carries

- [[Capacity]]
- [[Enter]]','Threshold Threshold names a boundary condition under strain where change becomes readable. It is not a measurement, line, or quantitative cutoff — it names the held change limit within the current scope of evaluation. Threshold sits between boundary, strain, and bearing: distinction is located, strain is present, and something is at the point where it can either hold or Shift without yet being determined either way. Places Threshold places a boundary condition under strain at the point where change becomes readable. Holds Threshold is held by Boundary and Strain. Distinction must be located and under contrast before its change limit can be read. Pairs Asymmetry carries downward — into Capacity and Enter. Threshold is the change limit under strain: it names the point where crossing becomes readable, not a lateral juncture requiring a co present condition. Traces Boundary Strain Shift Nests Threshold nests as a boundary condition. It sits between strain and bearing without becoming the crossing between orders by itself. Reads Threshold becomes recognisable where a boundary condition under strain can be read as change limit — where something is present at the point of potential shift without yet having crossed or entered it. Carries Capacity Enter','Threshold Threshold names a boundary condition under strain where change becomes readable. It is not a measurement, line, or quantitative cutoff — it names the held change limit within the current…','stable','rooted',0,'first','term',NULL,'[]','[]','["first.boundary","first.enter","first.shift","first.strain","second.capacity"]','{"holds":["first.boundary","first.strain"],"traces":["first.boundary","first.strain","first.shift"],"carries":["second.capacity","first.enter"],"pairs":["second.capacity","first.enter"],"nests":[],"reads":[]}','[{"depth":2,"text":"Places","anchor":"places"},{"depth":2,"text":"Holds","anchor":"holds"},{"depth":2,"text":"Pairs","anchor":"pairs"},{"depth":2,"text":"Traces","anchor":"traces"},{"depth":2,"text":"Nests","anchor":"nests"},{"depth":2,"text":"Reads","anchor":"reads"},{"depth":2,"text":"Carries","anchor":"carries"}]',198,'sha256:e2ab394c45640af6a091f2cbd3fded04d43ac97d2293cece7154cf7710fc111b','1970-01-01','2026-06-25');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO entries (id,title,slug,source_path,public_url,content,plain_text,excerpt,status,garden_status,grounded,entry_order,entry_type,branch,aliases,tags,related,structure,headings,word_count,content_hash,created,updated) VALUES ('first.time','Time','time','Reality_Mechanics/1_First/Relation Conditions/Time.md','https://atlas.realitymechanics.nz/time.html','# Time

Time names held clearance read as interval and continuation: relation persisting without collapsing into absolute self-sameness. Chronology, sequence, process, progression, and causation are later traversal reads. Time is clearance read as interval before any boundary marks it as sequence.

Downstream, time becomes readable as the rate and scale at which an order resolves. Different systems do not have different kinds of time first; they resolve held clearance at different rates and scales of order.

Recurring relation can make time measurable without producing Time. At human scale, temporal awareness is resolution-dependent: continuity may be carrying without being distinctly noticed, while [[Return]] provides a boundary at which that continuity becomes readable again. [[Cycle]] bounds the return, and [[Frequency]] counts returns per interval. These are downstream human-scale reads of Time, not replacements for its first-order placement.

## Places

Time places held clearance as interval and continuation.

## Holds

Time is held by [[Clearance]]. Relation must remain apart enough to continue without collapsing into static sameness.

## Pairs

Time pairs with [[Space]]. Time reads clearance as interval and continuation; Space reads clearance as separation and extent.

## Traces

- [[Clearance]]

## Nests

Time nests before chronology, sequence, process, progression, and causation. Those are later traversal reads of time, not the first condition.

## Reads

Time becomes recognisable where held clearance can be read as interval and continuation — where relation is present as persisting rather than as static sameness.

Humanly readable time changes with scale and resolution. When carrying crosses a boundary that a person can resolve — a beat, breath, pause, wait, interruption, completed operation, or recognised return — continuation becomes temporally distinct. When those boundaries fall below resolution or are carried implicitly, continuity may remain active while elapsed time becomes less noticeable.

This does not mean humans create Time or only encounter it through regular cycles. It means temporal awareness depends on which differences and returns can enter the participant''s current resolution band. When an order must be stepped through explicitly, sequence is visible and time may feel slow or granular. Where learning or sustained participation carries more of the order implicitly, sequence becomes less visible and time may feel more fluid.

## Carries

- [[Timescale]]
