"Holds","anchor":"holds"},{"depth":2,"text":"Pairs","anchor":"pairs"},{"depth":2,"text":"Traces","anchor":"traces"},{"depth":2,"text":"Nests","anchor":"nests"},{"depth":2,"text":"Reads","anchor":"reads"},{"depth":2,"text":"Carries","anchor":"carries"}]',152,'sha256:9b6ceb0d4062b724d22b4c2a5c43f3a6a4af78f45a0e477209d7ebd1b50ca1c8','1970-01-01','2026-06-25');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO entries (id,title,slug,source_path,public_url,content,plain_text,excerpt,status,garden_status,grounded,entry_order,entry_type,branch,aliases,tags,related,structure,headings,word_count,content_hash,created,updated) VALUES ('second.count','Count','count','Reality_Mechanics/2_Second/Produced Distinctions/Count.md','https://atlas.realitymechanics.nz/count.html','# Count

Count names recurrence held as how many through distinguishable units. Where [[Recurrence]] names participation occurring again and [[Unit]] names a bounded repeatable measure, count names the produced read through which repeated units can be held as quantity.

Count is not number by itself. Number may stabilise a count as a value, but count names the relation becoming readable as how many. Count also does not name measure by itself; measure compares a read against a unit or scale. Count depends on repeatable units; it does not ground them.

Count relates to [[Step]] where movement recurs as distinguishable units. A step may be counted, but step names answerable movement; count names the repeated units held as quantity.

## Places

Count places recurrence held as how many through distinguishable units.

## Holds

Count is held by [[Recurrence]] and [[Unit]].

## Pairs

Asymmetry carries downward. Count is a singular condition — recurrence made discrete through a unit. The asymmetry is expressed in what count carries: [[Number]] and [[Step]].

## Traces

- [[Recurrence]]
- [[Unit]]

## Nests

Count nests where recurrence and unit become readable as quantity within scope.

## Reads

Count becomes recognisable where repeated units can be held together as how many — where recurrence is not only returning, but becoming readable as quantity within scope.

## Carries

- [[Number]]
- [[Step]]','Count Count names recurrence held as how many through distinguishable units. Where Recurrence names participation occurring again and Unit names a bounded repeatable measure, count names the produced read through which repeated units can be held as quantity. Count is not number by itself. Number may stabilise a count as a value, but count names the relation becoming readable as how many. Count also does not name measure by itself; measure compares a read against a unit or scale. Count depends on repeatable units; it does not ground them. Count relates to Step where movement recurs as distinguishable units. A step may be counted, but step names answerable movement; count names the repeated units held as quantity. Places Count places recurrence held as how many through distinguishable units. Holds Count is held by Recurrence and Unit. Pairs Asymmetry carries downward. Count is a singular condition — recurrence made discrete through a unit. The asymmetry is expressed in what count carries: Number and Step. Traces Recurrence Unit Nests Count nests where recurrence and unit become readable as quantity within scope. Reads Count becomes recognisable where repeated units can be held together as how many — where recurrence is not only returning, but becoming readable as quantity within scope. Carries Number Step','Count Count names recurrence held as how many through distinguishable units. Where Recurrence names participation occurring again and Unit names a bounded repeatable measure, count names the…','stable','rooted',0,'second','term',NULL,'[]','[]','["practice.step","second.number","second.recurrence","second.unit"]','{"holds":["second.recurrence","second.unit"],"traces":["second.recurrence","second.unit"],"carries":["second.number","practice.step"],"pairs":["second.number","practice.step"],"nests":[],"reads":[]}','[{"depth":2,"text":"Places","anchor":"places"},{"depth":2,"text":"Holds","anchor":"holds"},{"depth":2,"text":"Pairs","anchor":"pairs"},{"depth":2,"text":"Traces","anchor":"traces"},{"depth":2,"text":"Nests","anchor":"nests"},{"depth":2,"text":"Reads","anchor":"reads"},{"depth":2,"text":"Carries","anchor":"carries"}]',210,'sha256:43a0aad3869e91895bd619acdca4be60a42ac58fe995aa5919212115d96d9a8a','1970-01-01','2026-06-25');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO entries (id,title,slug,source_path,public_url,content,plain_text,excerpt,status,garden_status,grounded,entry_order,entry_type,branch,aliases,tags,related,structure,headings,word_count,content_hash,created,updated) VALUES ('second.coupled-asymmetry','Coupled Asymmetry','coupled-asymmetry','Reality_Mechanics/2_Second/Presence Conditions/Coupled Asymmetry.md','https://atlas.realitymechanics.nz/coupled-asymmetry.html','# Coupled Asymmetry

Coupled asymmetry names resolved asymmetry held between coupled conditions. Where resolved asymmetry names a determined condition and coupling names resolved conditions held in relation, coupled asymmetry names the condition through which unevenness persists inside that coupling: each remains distinct while held together. Imbalance can show coupled asymmetry, but coupled asymmetry names difference remaining available within coupling, not failure of coupling.

## Places

Coupled Asymmetry places resolved asymmetry held between coupled conditions.

## Holds

Coupled Asymmetry is held by [[Resolved Asymmetry]] and [[Coupling]]. Asymmetry must be determined, and conditions must be held in relation, before unevenness can persist through coupling.

## Pairs

Asymmetry carries downward. Coupled Asymmetry is a singular condition — resolved asymmetry held together through coupling. There is no lateral contrast required at this level.

## Traces

- [[Resolved Asymmetry]]
- [[Coupling]]

## Nests

Coupled Asymmetry nests where asymmetry persists between coupled conditions without collapsing the coupling into sameness.

## Reads

Coupled asymmetry becomes recognisable where two coupled conditions can be read as uneven — where the coupling holds difference rather than resolving it into sameness.

## Carries','Coupled Asymmetry Coupled asymmetry names resolved asymmetry held between coupled conditions. Where resolved asymmetry names a determined condition and coupling names resolved conditions held in relation, coupled asymmetry names the condition through which unevenness persists inside that coupling: each remains distinct while held together. Imbalance can show coupled asymmetry, but coupled asymmetry names difference remaining available within coupling, not failure of coupling. Places Coupled Asymmetry places resolved asymmetry held between coupled conditions. Holds Coupled Asymmetry is held by Resolved Asymmetry and Coupling. Asymmetry must be determined, and conditions must be held in relation, before unevenness can persist through coupling. Pairs Asymmetry carries downward. Coupled Asymmetry is a singular condition — resolved asymmetry held together through coupling. There is no lateral contrast required at this level. Traces Resolved Asymmetry Coupling Nests Coupled Asymmetry nests where asymmetry persists between coupled conditions without collapsing the coupling into sameness. Reads Coupled asymmetry becomes recognisable where two coupled conditions can be read as uneven — where the coupling holds difference rather than resolving it into sameness. Carries','Coupled Asymmetry Coupled asymmetry names resolved asymmetry held between coupled conditions. Where resolved asymmetry names a determined condition and coupling names resolved conditions held in…','stable','rooted',0,'second','term',NULL,'[]','[]','["first.resolved-asymmetry","second.coupling"]','{"holds":["first.resolved-asymmetry","second.coupling"],"traces":["first.resolved-asymmetry","second.coupling"],"carries":[],"pairs":[],"nests":[],"reads":[]}','[{"depth":2,"text":"Places","anchor":"places"},{"depth":2,"text":"Holds","anchor":"holds"},{"depth":2,"text":"Pairs","anchor":"pairs"},{"depth":2,"text":"Traces","anchor":"traces"},{"depth":2,"text":"Nests","anchor":"nests"},{"depth":2,"text":"Re