d.structural-gathering","second.thing"]','{"holds":["second.form","second.carrying","first.relation"],"traces":["second.form","second.carrying","first.relation","second.medium","second.structural-gathering"],"carries":["second.strategy","second.stability","second.function","second.apparent-source","second.bearing-source","second.member","second.thing"],"pairs":["second.strategy","second.stability"],"nests":[],"reads":[]}','[{"depth":2,"text":"Places","anchor":"places"},{"depth":2,"text":"Holds","anchor":"holds"},{"depth":2,"text":"Pairs","anchor":"pairs"},{"depth":2,"text":"Traces","anchor":"traces"},{"depth":2,"text":"Nests","anchor":"nests"},{"depth":2,"text":"Reads","anchor":"reads"},{"depth":2,"text":"Carries","anchor":"carries"}]',222,'sha256:e5f1978d0ce3bcde5247e12915751e7e5666308b88350db3ab5c26ba379068dc','1970-01-01','2026-06-25');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO entries (id,title,slug,source_path,public_url,content,plain_text,excerpt,status,garden_status,grounded,entry_order,entry_type,branch,aliases,tags,related,structure,headings,word_count,content_hash,created,updated) VALUES ('second.surface','Surface','surface','Reality_Mechanics/2_Second/Produced Distinctions/Surface.md','https://atlas.realitymechanics.nz/surface.html','# Surface

Surface names the presenting face of a condition. Where [[Visible]] carries presented readability and [[Form]] names readable arrangement, Surface names the face through which that presentation is met, followed, trusted, patched, or mistaken as holding.

Surface can be shallow, false, decorative, or external, but it is not defined by those reductions. The surface presents. What matters is whether the presentation remains answerable to what carries it.

## Places

Surface places the presenting face of a condition.

## Holds

Surface is held by [[Visible]] and [[Form]].

## Pairs

Surface pairs with [[Kind]]: surface names the presenting face through which a condition becomes available; kind names the recurrent form recognisable across distinct instances of what presents. Each requires the other — surface is only surface if something of a kind is presenting; kind is only kind if it has surfaces through which it recurs.

## Traces

- [[Visible]]
- [[Form]]

## Nests

Surface nests as the presenting face of a condition. It can present truthfully, partially, or as mismatch depending on what carries it.

## Reads

Surface becomes recognisable where a condition presents a readable face — where what is available to read can be encountered before its carrying is fully traced.
## Carries

- [[Fabric]]
- [[Face]]
- [[Surface Patch]]
- [[Documentation Gap]]
- [[AI Drift]]','Surface Surface names the presenting face of a condition. Where Visible carries presented readability and Form names readable arrangement, Surface names the face through which that presentation is met, followed, trusted, patched, or mistaken as holding. Surface can be shallow, false, decorative, or external, but it is not defined by those reductions. The surface presents. What matters is whether the presentation remains answerable to what carries it. Places Surface places the presenting face of a condition. Holds Surface is held by Visible and Form. Pairs Surface pairs with Kind: surface names the presenting face through which a condition becomes available; kind names the recurrent form recognisable across distinct instances of what presents. Each requires the other — surface is only surface if something of a kind is presenting; kind is only kind if it has surfaces through which it recurs. Traces Visible Form Nests Surface nests as the presenting face of a condition. It can present truthfully, partially, or as mismatch depending on what carries it. Reads Surface becomes recognisable where a condition presents a readable face — where what is available to read can be encountered before its carrying is fully traced. Carries Fabric Face Surface Patch Documentation Gap AI Drift','Surface Surface names the presenting face of a condition. Where Visible carries presented readability and Form names readable arrangement, Surface names the face through which that presentation is…','stable','rooted',0,'second','term',NULL,'[]','[]','["first.visible","higher.fabric","second.face","second.form","second.kind","third.ai-drift","third.documentation-gap","third.surface-patch"]','{"holds":["first.visible","second.form"],"traces":["first.visible","second.form"],"carries":["higher.fabric","second.face","third.surface-patch","third.documentation-gap","third.ai-drift"],"pairs":["second.kind"],"nests":[],"reads":[]}','[{"depth":2,"text":"Places","anchor":"places"},{"depth":2,"text":"Holds","anchor":"holds"},{"depth":2,"text":"Pairs","anchor":"pairs"},{"depth":2,"text":"Traces","anchor":"traces"},{"depth":2,"text":"Nests","anchor":"nests"},{"depth":2,"text":"Reads","anchor":"reads"},{"depth":2,"text":"Carries","anchor":"carries"}]',202,'sha256:eeb380519a315cbb172e7d8a9512aa1d4985f66cbd4b1e5374ba0e5a749fc2bf','1970-01-01','2026-06-25');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO entries (id,title,slug,source_path,public_url,content,plain_text,excerpt,status,garden_status,grounded,entry_order,entry_type,branch,aliases,tags,related,structure,headings,word_count,content_hash,created,updated) VALUES ('second.tempo','Tempo','tempo','Reality_Mechanics/2_Second/Participation Conditions/Tempo.md','https://atlas.realitymechanics.nz/tempo.html','# Tempo

Tempo names rate carried as pace within rhythmic participation. Tempo does not name rhythm itself; it names how fast or slow the carried rhythm proceeds within a closure scope.

## Places

Tempo places rate carried as pace within rhythmic participation.

## Holds

Tempo is held by [[Rhythm]], [[Rate]], and [[Pace]].

## Pairs

Asymmetry carries downward. Tempo is a singular condition — rhythm measured as pace through rate. The asymmetry is expressed in what tempo carries: [[Learning Pace]].

## Traces

- [[Rhythm]]
- [[Rate]]
- [[Pace]]

## Nests

Tempo nests where rhythmic recurrence proceeds at a supportable rate within closure scope.

## Reads

Tempo becomes recognisable where rhythmic recurrence can be read as proceeding at a supportable rate.

## Carries

- [[Learning Pace]]','Tempo Tempo names rate carried as pace within rhythmic participation. Tempo does not name rhythm itself; it names how fast or slow the carried rhythm proceeds within a closure scope. Places Tempo places rate carried as pace within rhythmic participation. Holds Tempo is held by Rhythm, Rate, and Pace. Pairs Asymmetry carries downward. Tempo is a singular condition — rhythm measured as pace through rate. The asymmetry is expressed in what tempo carries: Learning Pace. Traces Rhythm Rate Pace Nests Tempo nests where rhythmic recurrence proceeds at a supportable rate within closure scope. Reads Tempo becomes recognisable where rhythmic recurrence can be read as proceeding at a supportable rate. Carries Learning Pace','Tempo Tempo names rate carried as pace within rhythmic participation. Tempo does not name rhythm itself; it names how fast or slow the carried rhythm proceeds within a closure scope.','stable','rooted',0,'second','term',NULL,'[]','[]','["second.pace","second.rate","second.rhythm","third.learning-pace"]','{"holds":["second.rhythm","second.rate","second.pace"],"traces":["second.rhythm","second.rate","second.pace"],"carries":["third.learning-pace"],"pairs":["third.learning-pace"],"nests":[],"reads":[]}','[{"depth":2,"text":"Places","anchor":"places"},{"depth":2,"text":"Holds","anchor":"holds"},{"depth":2,"text":"Pairs","anchor":"pairs"},{"depth":2,"text":"Traces","anchor":"traces"},{"depth":2,"text":"Nests","anchor":"nests"},{"depth":2,"text":"Reads","anchor":"reads"},{"depth":2,"text":"Carries","anchor":"carries"}]',112,'sha256:da742425b704993aa67ecc635a39d380aed537405b6d8760c20b8b002f78c26d','1970-01-01','2026-06-25');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO entries (id,title,slug,source_path,public_url,content,plain_text,excerpt,status,garden_status,grounded,entry_order,entry_type,branch,aliases,tags,related,structure,headings,word_count,content_hash,created,updated) VALUES ('second.terminal','Terminal','terminal','Reality_Mechanics/2_Second/Closure Conditions/Terminal.md','https://atlas.realitymechanics.nz/terminal.html','# Terminal

Terminal names the boundary where a read stops because continuation crosses a closure scope the current read cannot follow. Where threshold names a located condition that can hold or shift while reading continues, and a crossing hands a read off into the next register, terminal names where reading ends while bearing continues unread beyond the available scale. A terminal is not an end: what is carried continues past it. It names the limit of readability at the current closure scope, not the limit of carrying.

## Places

Terminal places the boundary where a read stops because continuation crosses a closure scope the current read cannot follow.

## Holds

Terminal is held by [[Thread]], [[Closure Scope]], and [[Boundary]].

## Pairs

[[Thread]] carries downward — into Terminal. Terminal names where the followable strand can no longer continue as the same read: where continuation crosses a closure scope the current read cannot follow.

## Traces

- [[Thread]]
- [[Closure Scope]]
- [[Boundary]]

## Nests

Terminal nests where the current closure scope cannot follow continuation though carrying continues beyond it.

## Reads

Terminal becomes recognisable where a read can no longer be followed across a boundary, not because carrying has ceased, but because continuation has crossed into a closure scope unavailable to the current read.
## Carries

- [[Collapse]]
- [[Order-Terminal]]
- [[Translation Boundary]]

## Order-Terminal

Order-terminal names terminal relative to an order. It is the condition where a readable length completes within its order and cannot continue as the same read without re-entry, restart, or lifting into another order. Order-terminal does not mean the order is dead or final; it means the current read has reached the limit at which continuing changes the kind of passage being read.','Terminal Terminal names the boundary where a read stops because continuation crosses a closure scope the current read cannot follow. Where threshold names a located condition that can hold or shift while reading continues, and a crossing hands a read off into the next register, terminal names where reading ends while bearing continues unread beyond the available scale. A terminal is not an end: what is carried continues past it. It names the limit of readability at the current closure scope, not the limit of carrying. Places Terminal places the boundary where a read stops because continuation crosses a closure scope the current read cannot follow. Holds Terminal is held by Thread, Closure Scope, and Boundary. Pairs Thread carries downward — into Terminal. Terminal names where the followable strand can no longer continue as the same read: where continuation crosses a closure scope the current read cannot follow. Traces Thread Closure Scope Boundary Nests Terminal nests where the current closure scope cannot follow continuation though carrying continues beyond it. Reads Terminal becomes recognisable where a read can no longer be followed across a boundary, not because carrying has ceased, but because continuation has crossed into a closure scope unavailable to the current read. Carries Collapse Order Terminal Translation Boundary Order Terminal Order terminal names terminal relative to an order. It is the condition where a readable length completes within its order and cannot continue as the same read without re entry, restart, or lifting into another order. Order terminal does not mean the order is dead or final; it means the current read has reached the limit at which continuing changes the kind of passage being read.','Terminal Terminal names the boundary where a read stops because continuation crosses a closure scope the current read cannot follow. Where threshold names a located condition that can hold or…','stable','rooted',0,'second','term',NULL,'[]','[]','["first.boundary","first.thread","second.closure-scope","second.collapse","second.order_terminal","third.translation-boundary"]','{"holds":["first.thread","second.closure-scope","first.boundary"],"traces":["first.thread","second.closure-scope","first.boundary"],"carries":["second.collapse","second.order_terminal","third.translation-boundary"],"pairs":[],"nests":[],"reads":[]}','[{"depth":2,"text":"Places","anchor":"places"},{"depth":2,"text":"Holds","anchor":"holds"},{"depth":2,"text":"Pairs","anchor":"pairs"},{"depth":2,"text":"Traces","anchor":"traces"},{"depth":2,"text":"Nests","anchor":"nests"},{"depth":2,"text":"Reads","anchor":"reads"},{"depth":2,"text":"Carries","anchor":"carries"},{"depth":2,"text":"Order-Terminal","anchor":"order-terminal"}]',277,'sha256:2ef57c12d28c622ae8d814b6260c92f5cee23005a7145084f566a126ddb9094a','1970-01-01','2026-06-25');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO entries (id,title,slug,source_path,public_url,content,plain_text,excerpt,status,garden_status,grounded,entry_order,entry_type,branch,aliases,tags,related,structure,headings,word_count,content_hash,created,updated) VALUES ('second.thing','Thing','thing','Reality_Mechanics/2_Second/Produced Distinctions/Thing.md','https://atlas.realitymechanics.nz/thing.html','# Thing

Thing names a scale-local stability of relation: held together by smaller relations, participating in larger relations, and readable at the scale where it can be named, used, or carried.

A thing-read can drift where a relation compressed into a noun is treated as if the noun must contain the whole referent. The dropped conditions were dropped from the description, not from reality. The repair is not to hunt for a hidden object inside the noun, but to reopen the relation, scale, and closure scope that made the thing readable.

## Places

Thing places a scale-local stability of relation.

## Holds

Thing is held by [[Stability]], [[Scale]], [[Relative]], [[Closure Scope]], [[Structure]], and [[Readability]]. Relation must hold together as structure, remain stable enough at a scale, be placed through relation, close locally enough for evaluation, and become readable before it can be named or carried as a thing.

## Pairs

No lateral pair is required at this placement yet. Thing currently reads as a scale-local stability between relations below it and relations above it.

## Traces

- [[Stability]]
- [[Scale]]
- [[Relative]]
- [[Closure Scope]]
- [[Structure]]
- [[Readability]]

## Nests

Thing nests where smaller relations hold together sufficiently for larger relations to depend on them at a readable scale and closure scope.

## Reads

Thing becomes readable where a relational stability can be named, used, carried, or depended on at the scale and scope where it holds.

This preserves usefulness without isolating the object. A beam is still a beam at the building scale and within the closure scope of building action. It is also fibres, bonds, grain, stress, moisture, fixings, and load path at other scales and scopes. The thing-read holds where the scale-local stability is real enough to carry participation.

The identity of a thing is therefore relative in the structural sense: not arbitrary, but placed through the relations that compose it, the relations it participates in, and the closure scope where it is being read.

When relation is nominalized, this carrying can become hidden. Re-entering the thing-read means asking what relation, scale, and closure scope the name has compressed. [[Relative]] keeps the object-read answerable to the relation and scope that placed it.

## Carries

Thing carries [[Member]] where a scale-local stability is read by the role it plays inside a wider carried body.

- [[Member]]','Thing Thing names a scale local stability of relation: held together by smaller relations, participating in larger relations, and readable at the scale where it can be named, used, or carried. A thing read can drift where a relation compressed into a noun is treated as if the noun must contain the whole referent. The dropped conditions were dropped from the description, not from reality. The repair is not to hunt for a hidden object inside the noun, but to reopen the relation, scale, and closure scope that made the thing readable. Places Thing places a scale local stability of relation. Holds Thing is held by Stability, Scale, Relative, Closure Scope, Structure, and Readability. Relation must hold together as structure, remain stable enough at a scale, be placed through relation, close locally enough for evaluation, and become readable before it can be named or carried as a thing. Pairs No lateral pair is required at this placement yet. Thing currently reads as a scale local stability between relations below it and relations above it. Traces Stability Scale Relative Closure Scope Structure Readability Nests Thing nests where smaller relations hold together sufficiently for larger relations to depend on them at a readable scale and closure scope. Reads Thing becomes readable where a relational stability can be named, used, carried, or depended on at the scale and scope where it holds. This preserves usefulness without isolating the object. A beam is still a beam at the building scale and within the closure scope of building action. It is also fibres, bonds, grain, stress, moisture, fixings, and load path at other scales and scopes. The thing read holds where the scale local stability is real enough to carry participation. The identity of a thing is therefore relative in the structural sense: not arbitrary, but placed through the relations that compose it, the relations it participates in, and the closure scope where it is being read. When relation is nominalized, this carrying can become hidden. Re entering the thing read means asking what relation, scale, and closure scope the name has compressed. Relative keeps the object read answerable to the relation and scope that placed it. Carries Thing carries Member where a scale local stability is read by the role it plays inside a wider carried body. Member','Thing Thing names a scale local stability of relation: held together by smaller relations, participating in larger relations, and readable at the scale where it can be named, used, or carried. A…','stable','rooted',0,'second','term',NULL,'[]','[]','["second.closure-scope","second.member","second.readability","second.relative","second.scale","second.stability","second.structure"]','{"holds":["second.stability","second.scale","second.relative","second.closure-scope","second.structure","second.readability"],"traces":["second.stability","second.scale","second.relative","second.closure-scope","second.structure","second.readability"],"carries":["second.member"],"pairs":[],"nests":[],"reads":[]}','[{"depth":2,"text":"Places","anchor":"places"},{"depth":2,"text":"Holds","anchor":"holds"},{"depth":2,"text":"Pairs","anchor":"pairs"},{"depth":2,"text":"Traces","anchor":"traces"},{"depth":2,"text":"Nests","anchor":"nests"},{"depth":2,"text":"Reads","anchor":"reads"},{"depth":2,"text":"Carries","anchor":"carries"}]',384,'sha256:8e20e18dc0d24339c98e81baff5747b50a3738fbb577c4c61c91525584ad4add','1970-01-01','2026-06-25');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO entries (id,title,slug,source_path,public_url,content,plain_text,excerpt,status,garden_status,grounded,entry_order,entry_type,branch,aliases,tags,related,structure,headings,word_count,content_hash,created,updated) VALUES ('second.throughput','Throughput','throughput','Reality_Mechanics/2_Second/Carrying Conditions/Throughput.md','https://atlas.realitymechanics.nz/throughput.html','# Throughput

Throughput names flow measured through a boundary or medium at a rate. It does not name the value of what passes; it names how much carrying passes through a condition within an interval.

## Places

Throughput places flow measured through a boundary or medium at a rate.

## Holds

Throughput is held by [[Flow]], [[Rate]], and [[Boundary]].

## Pairs

Asymmetry carries downward. Throughput is a singular condition — flow measured through [[Rate]] at a [[Boundary]]. There is no lateral contrast required at this level.

## Traces

- [[Flow]]
- [[Rate]]
- [[Boundary]]

## Nests

Throughput nests inside flow as amount passing through a medium or boundary per interval.

## Reads

Throughput becomes recognisable where carrying through a medium or boundary can be measured as amount per interval.

## Carries','Throughput Throughput names flow measured through a boundary or medium at a rate. It does not name the value of what passes; it names how much carrying passes through a condition within an interval. Places Throughput places flow measured through a boundary or medium at a rate. Holds Throughput is held by Flow, Rate, and Boundary. Pairs Asymmetry carries downward. Throughput is a singular condition — flow measured through Rate at a Boundary. There is no lateral contrast required at this level. Traces Flow Rate Boundary Nests Throughput nests inside flow as amount passing through a medium or boundary per interval. Reads Throughput becomes recognisable where carrying through a medium or boundary can be measured as amount per interval. Carries','Throughput Throughput names flow measured through a boundary or medium at a rate. It does not name the value of what passes; it names how much carrying passes through a condition within an interval.','stable','rooted',0,'second','term',NULL,'[]','[]','["first.boundary","second.flow","second.rate"]','{"holds":["second.flow","second.rate","first.boundary"],"traces":["second.flow","second.rate","first.boundary"],"carries":[],"pairs":["second.rate","first.boundary"],"nests":[],"reads":[]}','[{"depth":2,"text":"Places","anchor":"places"},{"depth":2,"text":"Holds","anchor":"holds"},{"depth":2,"text":"Pairs","anchor":"pairs"},{"depth":2,"text":"Traces","anchor":"traces"},{"depth":2,"text":"Nests","anchor":"nests"},{"depth":2,"text":"Reads","anchor":"reads"},{"depth":2,"text":"Carries","anchor":"carries"}]',120,'sha256:6950d18ce362081885a62b61849f8428dc84daf57e2d726698fdf89b104705b8','1970-01-01','2026-06-25');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO entries (id,title,slug,source_path,public_url,content,plain_text,excerpt,status,garden_status,grounded,entry_order,entry_type,branch,aliases,tags,related,structure,headings,word_count,content_hash,created,updated) VALUES ('second.traction','Traction','traction','Reality_Mechanics/2_Second/Coupling Conditions/Traction.md','https://atlas.realitymechanics.nz/traction.html','# Traction

Traction names grip becoming available for carrying through coupled contact. It is the condition through which carrying can proceed without slipping away from the support it needs. Connection and resistance can support traction, but traction names enough resistance to let carrying hold.

## Places

Traction places grip becoming available for carrying through coupled contact.

## Holds

Traction is held by [[Grip]], [[Coupled Contact]], and [[Carrying]].

## Pairs

Asymmetry carries downward. Traction is a singular condition — grip made into carrying through coupled contact. There is no lateral contrast required at this level.

## Traces

- [[Grip]]
- [[Coupled Contact]]
- [[Contact]]
- [[Carrying]]
- [[Friction]]

## Nests

Traction nests in carrying through coupled contact as the usable middle between slipping and stalling.

## Reads

Traction becomes recognisable where coupled contact and grip support carrying through resistance without detaching from support.

## Carries','Traction Traction names grip becoming available for carrying through coupled contact. It is the condition through which carrying can proceed without slipping away from the support it needs. Connection and resistance can support traction, but traction names enough resistance to let carrying hold. Places Traction places grip becoming available for carrying through coupled contact. Holds Traction is held by Grip, Coupled Contact, and Carrying. Pairs Asymmetry carries downward. Traction is a singular condition — grip made into carrying through coupled contact. There is no lateral contrast required at this level. Traces Grip Coupled Contact Contact Carrying Friction Nests Traction nests in carrying through coupled contact as the usable middle between slipping and stalling. Reads Traction becomes recognisable where coupled contact and grip support carrying through resistance without detaching from support. Carries','Traction Traction names grip becoming available for carrying through coupled contact. It is the condition through which carrying can proceed without slipping away from the support it needs.','stable','rooted',0,'second','term',NULL,'[]','[]','["first.contact","second.carrying","second.coupled-contact","second.friction","second.grip"]','{"holds":["second.grip","second.coupled-contact","second.carrying"],"traces":["second.grip","second.coupled-contact","first.contact","second.carrying","second.friction"],"carries":[],"pairs":[],"nests":[],"reads":[]}','[{"depth":2,"text":"Places","anchor":"places"},{"depth":2,"text":"Holds","anchor":"holds"},{"depth":2,"text":"Pairs","anchor":"pairs"},{"depth":2,"text":"Traces","anchor":"traces"},{"depth":2,"text":"Nests","anchor":"nests"},{"depth":2,"text":"Reads","anchor":"reads"},{"depth":2,"text":"Carries","anchor":"carries"}]',131,'sha256:959c553938fc5b58071dae79f9c3146d7055e7213601545b84129775a95c59cd','1970-01-01','2026-06-25');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO entries (id,title,slug,source_path,public_url,content,plain_text,excerpt,status,garden_status,grounded,entry_order,entry_type,branch,aliases,tags,related,structure,headings,word_count,content_hash,created,updated) VALUES ('second.traversal','Traversal','traversal','Reality_Mechanics/2_Second/Closure Conditions/Traversal.md','https://atlas.realitymechanics.nz/traversal.html','# Traversal

Traversal names a read being followed through a closure scope. Where closure scope names the bounded extent within which a read holds, traversal names the movement through that extent: following reads, conditions, and traces within the current scope. Progress or direction can appear during traversal, but traversal first names following through what is available within scope.

## Places

Traversal places a read being followed through a closure scope.

## Holds

Traversal is held by [[Closure Scope]].

## Pairs

Asymmetry carries downward. Traversal is a singular condition through which closure scope is moved through. The lateral asymmetry appears in what traversal carries: [[Process]] ↔ [[Sequence]].

## Traces

- [[Closure Scope]]

## Nests

Traversal nests where reads can be followed through available conditions within a bounded extent.

## Reads

Traversal becomes recognisable where reads can be followed through available conditions within a bounded extent — where movement through a scope is possible rather than merely presence within it.

## Carries

- [[Sequence]]
- [[Interval]]
- [[Change]]
- [[Speed]]
- [[Retrace Read|Retrace]]
- [[Recurrence]]
- [[Digress]]
- [[Velocity]]
- [[Field Bearing]]
- [[Moving]]','Traversal Traversal names a read being followed through a closure scope. Where closure scope names the bounded extent within which a read holds, traversal names the movement through that extent: following reads, conditions, and traces within the current scope. Progress or direction can appear during traversal, but traversal first names following through what is available within scope. Places Traversal places a read being followed through a closure scope. Holds Traversal is held by Closure Scope. Pairs Asymmetry carries downward. Traversal is a singular condition through which closure scope is moved through. The lateral asymmetry appears in what traversal carries: Process ↔ Sequence. Traces Closure Scope Nests Traversal nests where reads can be followed through available conditions within a bounded extent. Reads Traversal becomes recognisable where reads can be followed through available conditions within a bounded extent — where movement through a scope is possible rather than merely presence within it. Carries Sequence Interval Change Speed Retrace Read Recurrence Digress Velocity Field Bearing Moving','Traversal Traversal names a read being followed through a closure scope. Where closure scope names the bounded extent within which a read holds, traversal names the movement through that extent:…','stable','rooted',0,'second','term',NULL,'[]','[]','["second.change","second.closure-scope","second.digress","second.interval","second.process","second.recurrence","second.retrace-read","second.sequence","second.speed","second.velocity","third.field-bearing","third.moving"]','{"holds":["second.closure-scope"],"traces":["second.closure-scope"],"carries":["second.sequence","second.interval","second.change","second.speed","second.retrace-read","second.recurrence","second.digress","second.velocity","third.field-bearing","third.moving"],"pairs":["second.process","second.sequence"],"nests":[],"reads":[]}','[{"depth":2,"text":"Places","anchor":"places"},{"depth":2,"text":"Holds","anchor":"holds"},{"depth":2,"text":"Pairs","anchor":"pairs"},{"depth":2,"text":"Traces","anchor":"traces"},{"depth":2,"text":"Nests","anchor":"nests"},{"depth":2,"text":"Reads","anchor":"reads"},{"depth":2,"text":"Carries","anchor":"carries"}]',163,'sha256:62a99391c54952820f9423fe74ac61606ef4969b6ebd192e49bff0b21bb5dccf','1970-01-01','2026-06-25');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO entries (id,title,slug,source_path,public_url,content,plain_text,excerpt,status,garden_status,grounded,entry_order,entry_type,branch,aliases,tags,related,structure,headings,word_count,content_hash,created,updated) VALUES ('second.union','Union','union','Reality_Mechanics/2_Second/Union.md','https://atlas.realitymechanics.nz/union.html','# Union

Union names the invariant condition of genuine joining: distinct resolved conditions held together without collapsing into sameness.

[[Coupling]] names distinct resolved conditions held in mutual availability. Union is the prior condition coupling requires: the joining must be genuine before mutual availability can hold.

Union is not merger. Merger ends the distinction between joined conditions. Union holds the joining while distinction remains — joined-while-distinct is the structural signature of Union.

Union is also the condition that [[Decoupling]] presupposes. Decoupling names genuine joining no longer holding; without Union there is only separation of what was never genuinely joined.

Union is hidden in successful coupling because it is not the visible operation. It becomes clearest in its absence: where coupling fails despite apparent carrying, Union was not present.

## Places

Union places the invariant condition of genuine joining before the split into coupling and decoupling.

## Holds

Union is held by [[Carrying]]. Carrying must be established before distinct conditions can be genuinely joined.

## Pairs

Carrying carries downward — into Union. Union is an invariant carrier: it holds whether or not the split into coupling or decoupling is visible.

## Traces

- [[Carrying]]
- [[Invariant]]

## Nests

Union nests before the coupling/decoupling split. It lets coupling hold mutual availability and decoupling release genuine joining rather than mere separation.

## Reads

Union becomes recognisable where distinct resolved conditions are joined in a way that allows carrying to hold between them without collapsing into sameness.

It is also recognisable in absence: where carrying is present but mutual availability fails, the joining was not genuine.

## Carries

